'''Charles Cabrier II''' (18th century) was a notable London clock and scientific instrument maker.
== Biography == Charles Cabrier II, son of Charles I and father of Charles III, was the most prominent clockmaker of the three namesakes. The Cabriers were a celebrated dynasty of Huguenot clockmakers who settled in [[London]] after the Revocation of the [[Edict of Nantes]] (1685).<ref>[https://discoveringclocks.wordpress.com/2016/06/13/the-cabriers-huguenot-clockmakers-in-london/ The Cabriers: Huguenot Clockmakers in London]</ref> A relatively large number of their clocks - built over a period of half a century - have survived.<ref>[[Museo Galileo]]. "[http://catalogue.museogalileo.it/biography/CharlesCabrierII.html Charles Cabrier II]". Catalogue of the Museo Galileo's Instruments on Display. ''catalogue.museogalileo.it''</ref>
Apprenticed in 1719, Charles Cabrier II joined the [[Clockmakers' Company]] in 1726; he was [[Master craftsman|Master]] from 1757 to 1772.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=mch9CgAAQBAJ&lpg=PT28&ots=saLS_CDHPZ&dq=Charles%20Cabrier%20III&pg=PT28#v=onepage&q&f=false An Encyclopaedia of Famous Clock and Watchmakers]</ref> Many examples of his work, including table clocks, carriage clocks, and pocket watches, are preserved in collections and museums in [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Britain]] and [[America]], [[Germany]], [[Sweden]], and [[Russia]].
== Gallery == <gallery mode=packed caption="Clocks and watches by Charles Cabrier II" > File:Pair-case watch with repeating mechanism MET DP338579.jpg File:Pair-case watch with repeating mechanism MET DP340442.jpg File:Pair-case watch with repeating mechanism MET DP340674.jpg File:Watch MET DP-12739-092.jpg File:Clock-watch (part of a set) MET 40546.jpg File:Watch MET DP-12739-094.jpg </gallery>
