'''Joel Dudley''' is currently Associate Professor of Genetics and Genomic Sciences and founding Director of the Institute for Next Generation Healthcare at the [[Icahn School of Medicine at Mount Sinai]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mountsinai.org/profiles/joel-dudley |title=Joel Dudley - The Mount Sinai Hospital |website=The Mount Sinai Hospital |date=|accessdate=2017-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nextgenhealthcare.org/our-team/joel-t-dudley/ |title=Joel T. Dudley - Director, INGH |website=nextgenhealthcare.org |date=|accessdate=2017-12-11}}</ref> In March, 2018 Dr. Dudley was named Executive Vice President for Precision Health for the Mount Sinai Health System (MSHS). In 2017 he was awarded an Endowed Professorship by Mount Sinai in Biomedical Data Science. Prior to Mount Sinai, he held positions as Co-founder and Director of Informatics at NuMedii, Inc. and Consulting Professor of Systems Medicine in the Department of Pediatrics at Stanford University School of Medicine. His work is focused at the nexus of -omics, digital health, artificial intelligence (AI), scientific wellness, and healthcare delivery. His work has been featured in the Wall Street Journal, Scientific American, MIT Technology Review, CNBC, and other popular media outlets.<ref name="wsj1">{{cite news|author=Amy Dockser Marcus |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424053111903639404576514542144726276 |title=Researchers Show Gains in Finding Reusable Drugs |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=2011-08-24 |accessdate=2017-12-12}}</ref><ref name="scientificamerican1">{{cite news|author=Ariel Bleicher |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/demystifying-the-black-box-that-is-ai/ |title=Demystifying the Black Box That Is AI
 |magazine=[[Scientific American]] |date=2017-08-09 |accessdate=2017-12-12}}</ref><ref name="technologyreview1">{{cite news|author=Courtney Humphries |url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/518916/a-hospital-takes-its-own-big-data-medicine/ |title=A Hospital Takes Its Own Big-Data Medicine |magazine=[[MIT Technology Review]] |date=2013-09-26 |accessdate=2017-12-12}}</ref><ref name="cnbc1">{{cite web|author=Christine Wang |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/03/29/mt-sinai-researchers-to-share-theranos-study-data.html/ |title=Mt. Sinai researchers to share Theranos study data |publisher=[[CNBC]] |date=2016-03-29 |accessdate=2017-12-12}}</ref> He was named in 2014 as one of the 100 most creative people in business by Fast Company magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3027327/why-health-care-needs-creative-thinking-more-than-ever |title=Why Health Care Needs Creative Thinking More Than Ever |publisher=Fast Company |date= |accessdate=2017-12-12}}</ref> He is co-author of the book Exploring Personal Genomics from Oxford University Press.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/exploring-personal-genomics-9780199644490?cc=us&lang=en& |title=Exploring Personal Genomics |website=Oxford University Press |date=|accessdate=2017-12-12}}</ref> Dr. Dudley received a BS in Microbiology from Arizona State University and an MS and PhD in Biomedical Informatics from Stanford University School of Medicine.

